00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,440
Hello everyone

2
00:00:00,440 --> 00:00:01,280
I am Sui Yi

3
00:00:01,280 --> 00:00:03,120
This video discusses the gossip algorithm.

4
00:00:03,120 --> 00:00:06,180
This is the most renowned algorithm among broadcast algorithms.

5
00:00:06,180 --> 00:00:08,220
It is used in and applied to registration centers

6
00:00:08,220 --> 00:00:09,540
Consoredis

7
00:00:09,540 --> 00:00:14,460
as well as infrastructure like CASA database and Amazon's DOMO

8
00:00:14,460 --> 00:00:17,600
I found many incorrect statements about the Gossip algorithm online

9
00:00:17,600 --> 00:00:18,570
are all wrong

10
00:00:18,570 --> 00:00:20,410
First of all, it is not a consensus

11
00:00:20,410 --> 00:00:23,290
The algorithm also has nothing to do with eventual consistency

12
00:00:23,290 --> 00:00:26,380
even without any node failures

13
00:00:26,380 --> 00:00:28,049
data loss may also occur

14
00:00:28,049 --> 00:00:30,489
Let's first understand the broadcast algorithm

15
00:00:30,489 --> 00:00:32,129
As the name suggests, the broadcast algorithm

16
00:00:32,129 --> 00:00:35,270
is to distribute data from one node to multiple nodes

17
00:00:35,270 --> 00:00:37,690
For example, when I package a Docker image

18
00:00:37,690 --> 00:00:40,629
or distribute a Spark binary package

19
00:00:40,629 --> 00:00:44,749
or even sending a Messages to the lobby in a game

20
00:00:44,749 --> 00:00:48,690
These actions can be regarded as a broadcast algorithm

21
00:00:48,690 --> 00:00:51,690
Among them, the most common broadcast algorithm is a node

22
00:00:51,690 --> 00:00:54,120
send the value to all nodes

23
00:00:54,120 --> 00:00:56,840
From this perspective, the master-slave synchronization in databases

24
00:00:56,840 --> 00:01:00,280
synchronize messages from the master node of the keeper to the slave nodes

25
00:01:00,280 --> 00:01:02,710
can all be regarded as a type of gossip algorithm

26
00:01:02,710 --> 00:01:04,470
we refer to this one node

27
00:01:04,470 --> 00:01:07,530
a broadcast algorithm that sends messages to all other nodes

28
00:01:07,530 --> 00:01:10,210
collectively referred to as the gossip algorithm

29
00:01:10,210 --> 00:01:11,770
However, the problem with this algorithm is

30
00:01:11,770 --> 00:01:13,890
a bottleneck at a single node may occur

31
00:01:13,890 --> 00:01:16,670
When a node propagates messages to multiple nodes

32
00:01:16,670 --> 00:01:20,170
the deleted traffic is also the outgoing traffic from the server

33
00:01:20,170 --> 00:01:23,190
The traffic of messages is always the bottleneck

34
00:01:23,190 --> 00:01:24,470
after all, in the network

35
00:01:24,470 --> 00:01:26,790
Both uplink and downlink bandwidth are limited

36
00:01:26,790 --> 00:01:31,280
and the CPU copies the data to the network buffer in the kernel

37
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:32,950
there will also be some overhead

38
00:01:32,950 --> 00:01:35,270
such as the Eureka we learned in second grade

39
00:01:35,270 --> 00:01:36,370
uses this algorithm

40
00:01:36,370 --> 00:01:37,550
That's why

41
00:01:37,550 --> 00:01:39,210
the performance of eureka is not very good

42
00:01:39,210 --> 00:01:43,080
a performance bottleneck may occur when there are too many nodes

43
00:01:43,080 --> 00:01:46,260
So how can we reduce the pressure on the broadcast nodes?

44
00:01:46,260 --> 00:01:47,940
a very simple idea

45
00:01:47,940 --> 00:01:50,680
that is, we send messages to other nodes and then

46
00:01:50,680 --> 00:01:53,160
let other nodes help forward the message

47
00:01:53,160 --> 00:01:55,640
spread the broadcast message like wildfire

48
00:01:55,640 --> 00:01:58,000
In this way, each node makes good use of

49
00:01:58,000 --> 00:01:59,080
its own outgoing bandwidth

50
00:01:59,080 --> 00:02:02,610
The execution speed of the entire broadcast algorithm will not be too slow.

51
00:02:02,610 --> 00:02:07,900
So how do you choose which nodes to broadcast to?

52
00:02:07,900 --> 00:02:11,200
The UNIP algorithm answers by selecting randomly

53
00:02:11,200 --> 00:02:13,600
You can select in the network

54
00:02:13,600 --> 00:02:17,300
send data to any node you know

55
00:02:17,300 --> 00:02:21,020
Then all nodes in the cluster perform similar actions

56
00:02:21,020 --> 00:02:23,590
until the entire cluster receives the message

57
00:02:23,590 --> 00:02:24,430
Hearing this

58
00:02:24,430 --> 00:02:26,070
The audience might wonder

59
00:02:26,070 --> 00:02:28,530
Is it possible for the propagation path to form a loop?

60
00:02:28,530 --> 00:02:31,519
For example, A sends to B, and after B receives it, it sends back to A.

61
00:02:31,519 --> 00:02:31,999
Exactly

62
00:02:31,999 --> 00:02:34,879
To prevent information from being propagated indefinitely

63
00:02:34,879 --> 00:02:37,700
We usually only process the first received message

64
00:02:37,700 --> 00:02:42,079
In the diagram, the red lines actually represent redundant message propagation

65
00:02:42,079 --> 00:02:43,279
In addition

66
00:02:43,279 --> 00:02:45,199
If the message is prematurely completed

67
00:02:45,199 --> 00:02:49,690
So, are some nodes destined to never receive the message?

68
00:02:50,010 --> 00:02:53,230
Here we assume that each node after receiving the message

69
00:02:53,230 --> 00:02:54,690
sent to K nodes

70
00:02:54,690 --> 00:02:56,950
In this graph, this K is two

71
00:02:56,950 --> 00:02:58,410
Based on probability calculation

72
00:02:58,410 --> 00:03:00,830
When there are N nodes in the cluster

73
00:03:00,830 --> 00:03:02,730
and K needs to be greater than log n

74
00:03:02,730 --> 00:03:05,829
this type of message has a higher probability of being sent to all nodes

75
00:03:05,829 --> 00:03:08,130
Doesn't it sound quite unreliable?

76
00:03:08,130 --> 00:03:08,730
Exactly

77
00:03:08,730 --> 00:03:12,250
This unreliable protocol is actually the most commonly used broadcast protocol today

78
00:03:12,250 --> 00:03:13,590
Therefore, we find that

79
00:03:13,590 --> 00:03:18,220
whether it's Consul, Redis, Cassandra, or DynamoDB

80
00:03:18,220 --> 00:03:20,180
the gossip algorithm they use

81
00:03:20,180 --> 00:03:22,860
are only used for metadata updates and service discovery

82
00:03:22,860 --> 00:03:24,820
taking Redis as an example

83
00:03:24,820 --> 00:03:28,480
The data replication between master and slave still adopts the flooding strategy

84
00:03:28,480 --> 00:03:31,670
which means the master node sends all data to the slave nodes

85
00:03:31,670 --> 00:03:34,430
Only the service discovery part uses gossip

86
00:03:34,430 --> 00:03:37,010
In other words, they possess the following characteristics

87
00:03:37,010 --> 00:03:40,890
First, the overall data volume is not too large

88
00:03:40,890 --> 00:03:43,750
Secondly, there's no need to ensure message reliability.

89
00:03:43,750 --> 00:03:47,010
3. Requires complete decentralization

90
00:03:47,740 --> 00:03:50,300
For example, when you detect a node failure

91
00:03:50,300 --> 00:03:53,600
You inform other nodes about this through gossip

92
00:03:53,600 --> 00:03:58,150
However, some nodes were not notified of this in a timely manner

93
00:03:58,150 --> 00:03:59,190
No problem

94
00:03:59,190 --> 00:04:03,230
In the next round, other nodes may still send gossip

95
00:04:03,230 --> 00:04:06,910
notify this overlooked node of the latest cluster status

96
00:04:13,220 --> 00:04:15,800
actually, each node at fixed intervals

97
00:04:15,800 --> 00:04:18,539
randomly select a group of nodes to exchange differential data

98
00:04:18,539 --> 00:04:21,419
thus most nodes missed by the gossip

99
00:04:21,419 --> 00:04:24,289
can reacquire the corresponding messages

100
00:04:24,289 --> 00:04:25,289
but obviously

101
00:04:25,289 --> 00:04:28,369
if your data volume involves a database with millions of records

102
00:04:28,369 --> 00:04:30,369
This is clearly an unrealistic operation

103
00:04:30,369 --> 00:04:33,570
After all, this is essentially a full data synchronization

104
00:04:33,570 --> 00:04:36,210
Therefore, gossip currently cannot be applied to

105
00:04:36,210 --> 00:04:39,159
database replication scenarios

106
00:04:39,159 --> 00:04:42,459
there are many aspects of the gossip protocol that can be optimized

107
00:04:45,439 --> 00:04:47,039
information that needs to be transmitted

108
00:04:47,039 --> 00:04:51,339
You can also dynamically set the deletion of the get value based on the cluster size.

109
00:04:51,339 --> 00:04:53,159
the gossip protocol is simple and easy to use

110
00:04:53,159 --> 00:04:56,280
and it doesn't require you to store all the nodes in the cluster

111
00:04:56,280 --> 00:04:57,220
can work

112
00:04:57,220 --> 00:05:00,440
Therefore, it is also widely used in blockchain scenarios.

113
00:05:00,440 --> 00:05:03,229
When you want to create a cluster

114
00:05:03,229 --> 00:05:05,709
without relying on critical components like ETCD

115
00:05:05,709 --> 00:05:07,629
you might use gossip for service discovery

